What this buys you
One file = one run. If the manifest is identical, the intended run is identical.
No hidden state: config + inputs + expected hashes are all bound here.
Orchestrator-friendly: Go can generate this JSON and drop it into a volume; Python consumes it.
How the kernel would be invoked (manifest-only)

Example (assuming you adapt the CLI to accept manifest-only and use outputs.* if present):

run-analysis \
  --manifest-in configs/experiment_manifest.RIC-LIGO-O4-001.json \
  --schema configs/ric_echo_search.schema.json

If you keep CLI --output / --manifest-out, you can omit outputs in the manifest and pass them via flags instead.

Minimal manifest (tightest possible)

If you want the bare minimum:

{
  "manifest_version": "ric.experiment_manifest.v1",
  "config": { "... full config object ..." },
  "bindings": {
    "inputs": {
      "h1": { "path": "/data/H1.hdf5", "sha256": "..." },
      "l1": { "path": "/data/L1.hdf5", "sha256": "..." }
    }
  }
}